all.name: saddled bichir
all.catch-phrase: Wow! A saddled bichir! And me without my tiny riding crop...

all.name: blowfish
all.catch-phrase: I caught a blowfish! I'm blown away!

all.name: puffer fish
all.catch-phrase: I caught a puffer fish! I thought you would be tougher, fish!

all.name: tadpole

all.name: horse mackerel

all.name: blue marlin

all.name: giant trevally
all.catch-phrase: I caught a giant trevally! Yeah, I'm pretty well-trevalled.

all.name: mahi-mahi
all.catch-phrase: I caught a mahi-mahi! It's all mahine-mahine.

all.name: saw shark
all.catch-phrase: I caught a saw shark! You could call it a sea saw!

all.name: Cyrano
all.saying: Don't punch your nose to spite your face.

all.name: Pango

all.name: Pinky
all.saying: Time spent with friends is time well spent.

all.name: Eugene

all.name: Walt

all.name: Bud

all.name: Elvis

all.name: Simon

all.name: Tammi
all.saying: Always be down to monkey around!

all.name: Bella
all.saying: A glamour shot is worth a thousand words.

all.name: Bree
all.saying: The gift says more about the giver.

all.name: ankylo skull
all.museum-phrase: Oho! Ankylosaurus was the herbivore hero, the grazing gladiator, the vegetarian barbarian of antiquity! Between its club-like tail, heavy armor, and honest-to-goodness SPIKES, it was a formidable beast! Can you keep a secret? I have even heard recent theories that it actively ATTACKED predators. Can you imagine such behavior in an herbivore? It simply beggars the imagination!

all.museum-phrase: Oho! Ankylosaurus was the herbivore hero, the grazing gladiator, the vegetarian barbarian of antiquity! all.name: anomalocaris
all.museum-phrase: Anomalocaris lived in the water long before the dinosaurs and are known for their, er, "distinctive" look. Flat bodies over three feet in length, bulging eyes like a...dragonfly, antennae like shrimp tails... They looked so peculiar that people originally thought they were multiple fossils stacked on top of each other! As a delightful side note, "anomalocaris" means "abnormal shrimp". Obviously this animal has a certain reputation in the scientific community!

all.name: archaeopteryx
all.museum-phrase: Archaeopteryx's feathers led many people to believe it was the progenitor of the birds, eh wot... Sadly, further evidence indicates it's likely not a direct ancestor—more an evolutionary "uncle", if you will. Every time a specimen is found, new theories pop up. And new relatives come to roost in the family tree!

all.name: archelon torso
all.museum-phrase: Ah, yes. Archelon. It was a sort of huge sea turtle. The largest thus far found, if you want to know. They were very sizable—some 13 feet long, with a shell the size of a small car... If you're into that sort of thing. They likely ate seaweed, shrimp, octopus, and possibly ammonites, given the era involved. It seems CERTAIN giant turtles had to be prima donnas and eat some of the oldest life forms on earth!

all.name: archelon torso
all.museum-phrase: Archelon. What a ferocious forager it must have been indeed!

all.name: diplo chest
all.museum-phrase: Good old Diplodocus, what would we do without you? This stout fellow embodied all the best in dinosaurs. Those sturdy legs, that magnificent tail, and, above all, that extraordinary neck! Did you know that its center of gravity was such that sitting up on its hind legs was probably easy? What's more, paired with its long neck, this ability greatly increased its reach for eating plants! Best of all, Diplodocus probably grew its entire life, having no "adult size". Would that we were all so gifted!

all.name: mammoth torso
all.museum-phrase: Ah, Mammoths, the bad boys—and girls!—of the ancient-mammal world. So woolly! So unkempt! They are, of course, most famous for their size, which could be up to 13 tons for the largest males. But they were subject to no one's rules, and some species were SMALLER than modern elephants! Scientists have pondered for years: were mammoths the COOLEST of all extinct species? Perhaps so!

all.name: right ptera wing
all.museum-phrase: The mighty Pteranodon! Among the very largest animals ever to fly, they were role models to us all. With a wingspan of over 23 feet in some cases, I find it simply stunning that they ever did more than glide! But fly they did, soaring dynamically and dramatically over land and sea! I wish I could have seen it...

all.name: shark-tooth pattern
all.museum-phrase: This shark-tooth pattern comes from the lower jaw of an ancient shark of the genus Helicoprion. Its teeth seem to have grown in a distinctive arrangement rather disturbingly termed a "tooth-whorl". I say "seem" because shark skeletons are made not of bone, but cartilage, except for their teeth. Consequently, their bodies are never preserved as fossils, and questions about their jaws remain unanswered. The size and placement in the stone of the shark's teeth are actually the only things we have to work with. Sometimes in research we must maintain a stiff upper lip, even in the absence of a stiff lower jaw!

all.name: T. rex torso
all.museum-phrase: I'd say that T. Rex is the 800-pound gorilla of the dinosaur world, but it likely weighed well over nine tons. This fearsome chap is practically synonymous with the word "dinosaur", and for good reason! At up to 42 feet long with banana-sized teeth, it was one of the largest carnivores ever to walk the earth. It's unclear how fast T. Rex was since estimates vary wildly... I am just relieved I will never have to escape one. Hoo.

all.name: trilobite
all.museum-phrase: Trilobites were ancient and extinct before the dinosaurs ever appeared! It boggles the mind! Hoo! They were also one of the most successful classes of animal ever, existing for over 300 million years. Some 50,000 species have been identified in sizes ranging from three millimeters to over two feet! Alas, that is the very limit of my enthusiasm for them, though, they look rather too much like bugs.

all.name: pearl oyster
all.catch-phrase: I got a pearl oyster! Aw, shucks. Don't clam up now!

all.name: mussel
all.catch-phrase: I got a mussel! It's been working out

all.name: whelk
all.catch-phrase: I got a whelk! Happy snails to ya.

all.name: turban shell
all.catch-phrase: I got a turban shell! It's totally TURB...ular!

all.name: abalone
all.catch-phrase: I got an abalone! Why do I want a sandwich now?

all.name: umbrella octopus
all.catch-phrase: I got an umbrella octopus! Too bad I'm already soaked.

all.name: vampire squid
all.catch-phrase: I got a vampire squid! A lot was at stake.

all.name: firefly squid
all.catch-phrase: I got a firefly squid! More like a glowswim squid.

all.name: gazami crab
all.catch-phrase: I got a gazami crab! What a gripping find!

all.name: Dungeness crab
all.catch-phrase: I got a Dungeness crab! Dun dun duuuun...geness.

all.name: spider crab
all.catch-phrase: I got a spider crab! Water bugs can rest easy.

all.name: tiger prawn
all.catch-phrase: I got a tiger prawn! I ain't lion!

all.name: sweet shrimp
all.catch-phrase: I got a sweet shrimp! It's being very considerate.

all.name: lobster
all.catch-phrase: I got a lobster! Lobjective complete.

all.name: banded dragonfly
all.catch-phrase: Whoo hoo! Did you see that? Did you? I caught a banded dragonfly!
all.description: These got their name because of their tigerlike banding and evasion skills.

all.name: ladybug
all.catch-phrase: I caught a ladybug! Sorry to disturb you, ma'am.
all.description: Also called ladybirds or lady beetles, these help gardens by controlling pests.

all.name: common butterfly
all.catch-phrase: I caught a common butterfly! They often flutter by!
all.description: Though all look white to the naked eye, males and females are different colors.

all.name: yellow butterfly
all.catch-phrase: I  caught a yellow butterfly! Shouldn't all BUTTERflies be yellow?
all.description: All males of the species are white- females can be yellow or white.

all.name: tiger butterfly
all.location: Flying near red and pink flowers
all.catch-phrase: I caught a tiger butterfly! I've earned my stripes!
all.description: Wherever there are orange trees, these butterflies are likely to be found.It features yellow and black-striped patterns, with a blue band on the bottom

all.name: academic painting
all.description: In the forgery, there is a coffee stain in the top right corner. The forgery also has a key taped to the back of the canvas. If there is no stain and key, it is genuine.

all.name: calm painting
all.artwork-name: A Sunday Afternoon on the Island of La Grande Jatte
all.description: This is an example of pointillism. The scene of the crowd is actually made entirely out of small dots.

all.name: common painting
all.description: This painting depicts a common scene of the day where extra wheat is collected by the needy.

all.name: detailed painting
all.description: The flowers are purple and no stamp and signature are on the left edge. If there are blue flowers and the stamp and signature are present, it is genuine.

all.name: dynamic painting
all.artwork-name: Thirty-Six Views of Mount Fuji The Great Wave off Kanagawa
all.description: This is the most famous piece in a series called the Thirty-Six Views, yet the actual total in the set is 46.

all.name: famous painting
all.description: The most famous smile in the world. No one quite knows to this very day why the woman is smiling.

all.name: flowery painting
all.description: Van Gogh painted this piece when he moved to the south of France in search of more vibrant colors. Yellow was Van Gogh's favorite color, and he made seven paintings that featured sunflowers during this time.

all.name: jolly painting
all.description: A curious portrait by Giuseppe Arcimboldo, an Italian painter from the late 16th century. It doesn't take a particularly sharp eye to see that the entire portrait is composed of fresh produce.

all.name: wistful painting
all.description: Also known as Girl with a Turban, this piece uses ultramarine paint, which was expensive at the time. It seems the expense was worth it, as the vivid blue colors draw the eye and help make the piece a classic. The only question is... Is that a real pearl earring? Or something else...

all.name: peacock butterfly
all.location: Flying near blue, purple, and black flowers
all.catch-phrase: I caught a peacock butterfly! Now it's my turn to strut my stuff!
all.description: Papilio bianor, or Chinese peacock, is a species of butterfly that is native to East Asia. The female has more prominent markings than the male, and is roughly 7-8 centimeters long. Caterpillars feed on Zanthoxylum (prickly-ash) and Phellodendron (cork tree) plants.

all.name: emperor butterfly
all.catch-phrase: I caught an emperor butterfly! It's not your average monarch!
all.description: Morpho menelaus, more commonly known as the Blue Morpho, is an exotic butterfly that can be found in Central and South America. It feeds primarily on rotten fruit, but in the larval stage, frequently eats other larvae of the same species.

all.name: long locust
all.catch-phrase: I caught a long locust! It got the short end of the stick!
all.description: It is naturally camouflaged by its green exterior and the green grass that surrounds it and will occasionally make a sound.

all.name: grasshopper
all.catch-phrase: I caught a grasshopper! No vacationing for these guys, even in the summer!
all.description: These eat until their stomachs bulge. When hungry, they may eat each other.

all.name: cricket
all.catch-phrase: I caught a cricket! That's a sticky wicket, isn't it?
all.description: These have ears—not on their heads, but on their front legs.

all.name: honeybee
all.catch-phrase: I caught a honeybee! Ah, sweet success!
all.description: All worker bees are female. Their honey has an almost indefinite shelf life.

all.name: wasp
all.catch-phrase: I caught a bee! Bzzz! Bzzz! Bzzz! Phew! ...But why am I still holding it?!
all.description: These poison-carrying bees will attack big foes to protect the queen.

all.name: giant cicada
all.catch-phrase: I caught a giant cicada! I guess it's PRETTY big...
all.description: As the name might indicate, giant cicadas are one of the largest species of cicada in the world. They used to live mostly in warmer western Japan, but they've now also moved to urban eastern Japan. Though they're now common in these areas, they aren't well known in other parts of the world.

all.name: cicada shell
all.catch-phrase: I found a cicada shell! I'm glad the little guy came out of it!
all.description: Cicada larvae emerge from the ground in the evening and molt on trees, leaving behind empty shells. It's possible to find out the species of cicadas just by looking at these shells. Collecting the shells will tell you how many and what kind of cicadas inhabit a certain area.

all.name: red dragonfly
all.catch-phrase: I caught a red dragonfly! Didn't even have to roll for initiative!
all.description: Ever looked into the eyes of a red dragonfly, or any dragonfly, for that matter? They've compound eyes, where multiple eyeballs are stuck together, wot! Just think of all those beady little eyes on you! Blech! How very vile... To be honest, bugs with only TWO eyes make me gag.

all.name: dung beetle
all.catch-phrase: I caught a dung beetle! This species likes feces!
all.description: These beetles are also known as scarabs and were once revered in some parts of the world. Looking at it now, I must admit there IS something a bit refined about its antennae and legs...

all.name: scarab beetle
all.catch-phrase: I  caught a scarab beetle! It's just a dung beetle with better hobbies.
all.description: From the gorgeous to the grotesque, the fruit-beetle family has a wide variety of members, indeed... Among them, the shiniest by far is the scarab beetle. Not that it makes any bit of difference to me. If it has antennae, it's most unconscionably vile...

all.name: ant
all.catch-phrase: I caught an ant! TELL ME WHERE THE QUEEN IS!
all.description: Twenty percent of worker ants actually don't do anything... They are lazy ants.

all.name: snail
all.catch-phrase: I caught a snail! Seriously, though... Could you fail to catch a snail?
all.description: They have tiny, tiny teeth--20,000 of them--which they scrape across their food to eat.

all.name: centipede
all.catch-phrase: I caught a centipede! 99 more and I'll have a dollarpede!
all.description: Very few of these actually have more than 100 legs. They have nasty bites.

all.name: spider
all.catch-phrase: I caught a spider! Look at all those eyes!
all.description: They have eight legs. Their heads and chests are connected. Baby spiders can spin thread to fly.

all.name: tarantula
all.catch-phrase: I caught a tarantula! Don't try this at home!
all.description: Their poison isn't potent enough to be lethal, but their belly hair causes itchiness.

all.name: scorpion
all.catch-phrase: I caught a scorpion! It looks kind of crabby to me...
all.description: Their tail is actually part of their stomach.

all.name: sea grapes
all.catch-phrase: I got some sea grapes! Can't let these go sour.
all.description: Sea grapes are small spheres attached to slender stems on branches, similar to normal grapes. However, despite looking like and being called grapes, they aren't much like the land-based variety. They grow in warm oceans and are very susceptible to cold conditions, meaning refrigeration is difficult.

all.name: moon jellyfish
all.catch-phrase: I caught a jellyfish! Now all I need is a peanut-butter fish.
all.description: These plankton have a vicious sting!

all.name: sea star
all.catch-phrase: I got a sea star! Is a group called a constellation?
all.description: These star-shaped creatures have hundreds of tiny feet attached to their mobile arms. This allows them to slowly walk and open shellfish for food, making them effective predators. If an arm gets caught and ripped off by another predator, the sea star's arm will just grow back. Some sea stars eat by extending their stomachs out of their mouths to trap and then digest prey.
